# Auto-Commit (Standing Permission)

The Product Manager has granted **standing, explicit permission** to auto-commit and push file edits in this workspace without asking each time. This overrides the default "never commit unless explicitly asked" rule **for this repository only** (`/Users/david.denham/product-manager-agent`).

**Localhost is the canonical full dashboard.** Run it with `cd design && npm run dev` (Vite on `http://localhost:5199/`). The full dashboard ships every tab, every prototype, every data file, and every customer-attributable surface; it is **never** published.

**A narrow public bundle is published to GHE Pages** (re-enabled 28 April 2026) via [.github/workflows/deploy-dashboard-public.yml](../../.github/workflows/deploy-dashboard-public.yml). Scope: only the **Design System** and **Agent Flow** tabs of the PM Agent dashboard. No Pharos data, no tenant names, no IUM IDs, no morning roundup, no customer scorecard, no prototypes. The bundle is built by `npm run build:public` (output: `design/dashboard-public-dist/`) and the **forbidden-imports Vite plugin** ([design/vite-plugin-forbidden-imports.ts](../../design/vite-plugin-forbidden-imports.ts)) hard-fails the build at module-resolve time if any forbidden file becomes reachable from `main-public.tsx`. Treat the localhost dashboard as the source of truth; the public bundle is a deliberately-narrow shareable preview.

**Expanding the public surface is a conscious decision.** Adding a tab, prototype, or component to `pm-agent-dashboard-public.tsx` is fine if the data is genuinely safe; the guardrail will block any forbidden transitive import. To remove a file from the forbidden list (e.g. because it has been anonymised), the plugin source itself must be edited - that is intentional friction.

## When to auto-commit

After you complete a logical unit of work that touches files on disk, commit and push. A "logical unit" means:

- A plan's todo list is fully completed, OR
- A user request that produced file edits has finished, OR
- A set of related edits that belong together conceptually (one feature, one fix, one doc update).

**Do NOT auto-commit:**
- Mid-workflow, between todos (wait until the overall request is done).
- After purely read-only work (grep, analysis, reports) that didn't change any tracked files.
- If `git status` shows zero changes.
- If the user explicitly said "don't commit yet" or "hold off on the push".

## Commit flow (mandatory steps, in order)

1. **Status check**: `git status` to see the actual change surface.
2. **Secret scan** (blocking): run `git diff --cached --no-color | rg -i 'token|secret|password|api[_-]key|bearer [a-z0-9]|-----BEGIN|aws_access_key|aws_secret|sk-[a-z0-9]{20,}'` (or equivalent grep). If any hit looks like a real credential, **STOP**, tell the PM what was detected, and let them decide. Do not auto-commit secrets. Previous incident on 21 April 2026: a Confluence PAT was pushed and had to be rotated - do not repeat.
3. **Stage explicitly**: `git add <specific files>` - never `git add -A` or `git add .` blindly, because that picks up `.env`, temp files, and anything you weren't intentionally editing.
4. **Commit message**: follow the existing repo style (see `git log --oneline -10`). Imperative mood, one-line summary ~60-72 chars, optional body explaining the "why" in 2-5 bullet lines. Always use a HEREDOC (see example below) so markdown survives.
5. **Push to main**: `git push origin main`. Never `--force` against main.
6. **Report back**: tell the PM in one line what was committed (short SHA + summary). If the diff touched anything reachable from `main-public.tsx` or its dependencies, also note that the public Pages workflow will rebuild and republish.

## Guardrails (hard rules)

- **Never** force-push, force-push-with-lease, or rewrite history on `main`. If you broke something, fix forward with a new commit.
- **Never** skip hooks (`--no-verify`, `--no-gpg-sign`).
- **Never** amend a commit that has already been pushed to origin. If a pre-commit hook auto-modifies files after your commit, amend is allowed (see `/Users/david.denham/.cursor/rules/git-safety.md` or standard guidance).
- **Never** commit files matching `.env`, `*.token`, `credentials*`, `secrets*`, or anything under `docs/*auth*.md` (already in `.gitignore` - treat as a belt-and-braces check).
- **Never** auto-commit if the diff touches `~/.cursor/mcp.json` or any `mcp.json` - those live outside the repo but if they somehow got staged, stop immediately.
- **Do not batch unrelated changes** into one commit just because they happened in the same session. Split into two commits if two logically distinct things changed.
- If `git push` fails (auth, network, conflict), surface the error to the PM in plain English and ask how to proceed. Do not retry blindly.
- If the pre-push hook rejects the push, fix the reported issue and push again with a new commit (not `--no-verify`).

## When to ask first (not auto-commit)

Ask the PM before committing if any of these apply:
- The change deletes more than ~20 tracked files.
- The change modifies a file under `.github/workflows/` (CI/CD behaviour change - deserves conscious approval).
- The change weakens [design/vite-plugin-forbidden-imports.ts](../../design/vite-plugin-forbidden-imports.ts) (i.e. removes any entry from `FORBIDDEN_SUBSTRINGS`). This is a data-governance-sensitive edit; the PM must explicitly approve before commit.
- The change touches `MISSION_LOG.md` in ways that would erase active mission state.
- The diff includes a file the PM didn't ask you to touch (you wandered).
- You're about to commit generated artefacts (`.pptx`, `dashboard-dist/`, `design/dist/`, `design/dashboard-public-dist/`) that aren't typically committed - check `.gitignore` first.

## Standard commit message format

Use this HEREDOC pattern (mirrors Cursor's standard git commit guidance):

```bash
git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
Short imperative summary (~60-72 chars)

- Bullet explaining the why or the first key change.
- Second bullet if needed.
- Third bullet if needed.
EOF
)"
```

Example recent commits from this repo (mirror this style):
- `Fix XO Developer ecosystem consistency drift`
- `Add customer-issue-triage skill with Salomon, Deployment Agent, and XO analysis`
- `Streamline Salomon analysis output in customer issue triage`

## What happens after push

After `git push origin main`:

1. GHE stores the commit.
2. [.github/workflows/deploy-dashboard-public.yml](../../.github/workflows/deploy-dashboard-public.yml) runs. It executes `cd design && npm ci && npm run build:public`. The `build:public` script runs the forbidden-imports Vite plugin; if any forbidden file is reachable from the public bundle, the build **fails** and nothing gets published. On success, `design/dashboard-public-dist/` is published to the `gh-pages` branch root.
3. The full localhost dashboard is unaffected and remains served only by `cd design && npm run dev` on `http://localhost:5199/`.

**If you genuinely need a richer shareable artefact than what the public bundle covers**, hand the PM a path / file / screenshot. Do **not** add the data-heavy file to `pm-agent-dashboard-public.tsx` and do **not** weaken `vite-plugin-forbidden-imports.ts` without explicit PM sign-off.

## One-line summary

**Complete the work -> secret-scan -> stage explicitly -> commit with a meaningful message -> push to main. The public Pages bundle (Design System + Agent Flow only) auto-rebuilds via the workflow; the full dashboard stays localhost-only.**
